                        <summary>
                            
                            <p>On the north wall of the <hi rend="italic">maṇḍapa</hi> in front of the central shrine in the Chandramauḷīśvara temple.</p>						
                            
                            <p>Kulōttuṅgachōḷa I. Year 29: 1098-99 A.D.</p>						
                            
                            <p>This inscription commences with the <hi rend="italic">praśasti, Pugaḻmādu viḷaṅga</hi>, etc., of the king.</p>						
                            
                            <p>It records the dedication of the services of Aṅgāḍi, her daughter Pēraṅgāḍi and her descendants as <hi rend="italic">dēvaraḍiyār</hi> to god Mahādēva in Tiruvakkarai by Amudan Paḷḷikoṇḍān, Amudan Veḷān and Amudan Uyyavandāṉ, the first being referred to as a <hi rend="italic">veḷḷāḷa</hi> resident of Pandimaṅgalattu-ppāligaiyūr in Māttūr-nāḍu in Jayaṅgoṇḍaśōḻa-maṇḍalam. This document is endorsed by the first of the three donors who are evidently brothers on account of their patronymic Amudan. The other two of the signatories are apparently described as Rājaśikhāmaṇi-ppallavaraiyaṉ and as the Mūvēndavēḷān of Karikālaśōḻatteṉkarai-nāḍu, a member of the regiment called <hi rend="italic">Mudikoṇḍaśōḻatterinda villigaḷ</hi> respectively.</p>						
                            
                        </summary>
